Flames shot from Thassalin's jaws as the huge Thraki set a particular stretch of forest ablaze and then circled over it to detect movement. Strangely, the eerie screeching behind him ceased as he slowed down. Thassalin had forgotten the passengers on his back.
"What's this, Tenuk, you've turned into a Thraki before!"
"If I fly myself, it's completely different than suddenly being lifted up by a huge pink dragon!"
"It wasn't that bad, was it, Kayel?"
Kayel clearly did not share Nyssi's opinion. He looked less black than usual, and his claws had dug so deeply into Thassalin's back that the Thraki bled. Thassalin apparently didn't mind this, but he had come to realize that he had scared his new friends and landed in a clearing.
"I'M SORRY, BUT I SENSED SOMETHING. I HAD TO TAKE CARE OF THAT!"
"But did you have to drag us along too?" growled Tenuk as he climbed down from Thassalin's back and slid down to his tail. "And we left Retvik behind! Our big, strong fighter, we've abandoned him! How is he ever going to catch up to us again?"
"He'll figure something out..." growled Nyssi. "Retvik isn't the fastest, but he's not dumb."
"Sure, but can Retvik drive?"
Nyssi winked and turned back to Tenuk. "Of course he can drive."
"Have you ever seen Retvik drive a vehicle? He doesn't have a truck like you, and I've never seen him drive a nice little car like Kayel's. Plus, he only started taking the car for work because you always drive us. He only has a bicycle."
Loud laughter interrupted them. Thassalin suddenly found something incredibly funny, but no one knew what he was laughing at. It took a bit too long for Thassalin to calm down.
"I'M SORRY, BUT I IMAGINED YOUR GIANT FRIEND ARMORED UP ON SUCH A TINY LITTLE BIKE FOR TEMTHAN KIDS. THAT WAS PRICELESS! I WISH I HAD SOME KIND OF TELEPATHY. A MARVELOUS IMAGINATION! ONE I CAN'T SHARE!"
Kayel chuckled, figuring out what was going on in Thassalin's head. "Yeah, that's true. But what did you smell, and why did you suddenly take off?"
Thassalin grumbled, took off, and disappeared. When he returned after a short while, he threw something lifeless at Nyssi's feet. It was an Orothrack, a very rare, gold-white dragonlike creature. But it was missing its head. "ANOTHER DEAD ONE. I HEAR THEIR SCREAMS. SMELL THEIR BLOOD. SOMETHING DRIVES ME TO PROTECT AND HUNT. AS YISINI COMMANDS. THEY ARE VERY CLOSE."
The mighty Thraki suddenly froze. Nyssi and Kayel froze as well and looked intently toward a gap in the clearing. Something large and black stared at them and hissed. Whatever it was, it spread two enormous pairs of wings and shot toward Thassalin, paying no heed to the three smaller beings between them. Kayel and Tenuk just barely managed to take cover, but Nyssi was caught up and almost thrown onto Thassalin.
Thassalin reacted to this attack by grabbing Nyssi and hurling him onto his back with his incredibly long, skillful tail before he launched himself into the air. The black, two-winged creature pursued them at high speed.
Kayel snapped angrily as he took his rifle from his back and opened a pouch containing a bullet belt. He slung the belt over his chest, but quickly realized that Nyssi, the Thraki, and the monster were out of sight.
"Hey, Tenuk, could you transform into something that can fly?" asked Kayel.
"Do you want to follow them?"
"Yes, of course!"
"But... One of them is a huge monster!"
"Sure and what? I'm standing here with a top-notch rifle in my hand and could shoot right away. But, well, how should I put it – I would have to be able to see it in order to hit it."
Tenuk hesitated, then stepped back to make more room. With a soft, painful grunt, Tenuk's body stretched out, his fur turning into scales and his arms into wings. He quickly transformed into a normal, light-blue Thraki, but his eyes remained red.
"Get on."
Looking like an ordinary Thraki, Tenuk now had a decent scale shield running along his back. Fortunately, a pair of spines had also grown on his back, allowing Kayel to hold on. It took a little too long for Tenuk to get airborne, but once in the air, he quickly oriented himself and tried to resume the pursuit.
Tenuk and Kayel quickly realized they were not alone. A second dark creature shot up beneath them, and Tenuk could only barely avoid a collision.
"That must be the other fearsome giant monster that Lanex was afraid of?" Kayel furrowed his brow. He tried to shoot at the second beast, missed, and quickly reloaded.
Tenuk did not answer. He was too focused on concentrating on the flight toward Nyssi and Thassalin, even though the other creature was pursuing them. Kayel awkwardly turned around to keep the monster in sight. The fact that it was following them was an advantage for Kayel, as it made it easier for him to aim and fire. Two shots went through the upper wings of the creature. It let out a scream of pain and sank back under the trees. Kayel wasn't sure if it was still following them, but it certainly wouldn't be able to keep up with them.
A good distance ahead, Nyssi desperately clung on as Thassalin flailed around and spat fireballs at the blackened monster. The creature was definitely injured. It seemed extremely angry, but not willing to give in. The fireballs didn't seem to have the desired effect. As Thassalin stretched, Nyssi took the opportunity to draw her own weapon, an old shotgun. It wasn't exactly the first choice, but maybe the buckshot would scare off the black beast.
